00:05:12,565 --> 00:05:15,267
weaknesses of VR and are going to be built from the ground up.

96
00:05:15,327 --> 00:05:17,009
I'll talk a little bit more about that later.

97
00:05:17,670 --> 00:05:23,541
motion. It's really hard to get away from motion in VR. A lot of new experiences we're

98
00:05:23,961 --> 00:05:28,430
trying to avoid motion with teleporting or keeping you in a single physical space. But it's

99
00:05:28,450 --> 00:05:29,231
hard to get away from.

100
00:05:30,767 --> 00:05:34,410
So let's talk a little bit about why emotion is such a challenge. When your eyes and your

101
00:05:34,450 --> 00:05:38,894
vestibular system disagree, that's when you get sick. This is why roller coasters are such a

102
00:05:38,934 --> 00:05:42,737
bad idea. Your eyes are telling you one sense of acceleration, your ears are telling you

103
00:05:42,757 --> 00:05:45,960
another sense of acceleration. The time when those things tend to disagree is when you've

104
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:50,104
been poisoned or drunk and so our body responds in the same way as when you've been poisoned

105
00:05:50,144 --> 00:05:55,789
or drunk. One of the things you can do is minimize problems either with constant velocity.

106
00:05:56,409 --> 00:05:59,712
or by using blink teleportation. I'm going to dig into this more

107
00:05:59,752 --> 00:06:03,855
deeply. Typically when we're designing motion curves for a

108
00:06:03,895 --> 00:06:08,258
game experience in 2D or a website, whatever, we apply a

109
00:06:08,318 --> 00:06:09,239
constant acceleration.

110
00:06:10,110 --> 00:06:16,655
and this gives us a velocity curve like this. So you have your positive acceleration, you

111
00:06:16,715 --> 00:06:20,518
increase your velocity, you have your negative acceleration, you decrease your velocity and

112
00:06:20,538 --> 00:06:25,442
it gives you this nice smooth S curve of your position, looks about like this. And the thing

113
00:06:25,482 --> 00:06:31,887
to note about this is that your acceleration is always non-zero. So in this kind of situation

114
00:06:31,927 --> 00:06:36,811
your eyes are the entire time disagreeing with your inner ear about what your acceleration

115
00:06:36,911 --> 00:06:36,971
is.

116
00:06:37,532 --> 00:06:39,813
So instead, what we found in many cases is the best

117
00:06:39,833 --> 00:06:40,694
practices for VR.

118
00:06:40,714 --> 00:06:42,715
And again, I've seen these rules broken to great effect.

119
00:06:42,755 --> 00:06:46,177
But generally speaking, what we try to do is apply a

120
00:06:46,277 --> 00:06:49,299
constant velocity, which gives you an ugly looking position

121
00:06:49,339 --> 00:06:50,000
curve like this.

122
00:06:50,300 --> 00:06:52,021
But here's the key is that it gives you an acceleration

123
00:06:52,061 --> 00:06:52,902
curve that looks like this.

124
00:06:52,942 --> 00:06:55,403
You have this instantaneous impulse of positive

125
00:06:55,423 --> 00:06:57,725
acceleration, this instantaneous impulse of

126
00:06:57,785 --> 00:07:01,447
negative acceleration, and most of the time, your eyes

127
00:07:01,467 --> 00:07:03,769
and your inner ear agree about what the acceleration is.

128
00:07:04,209 --> 00:07:05,410
So this tends to work pretty well.

129
00:07:06,030 --> 00:07:07,993
The other thing you can do is blink teleport. So basically

130
00:07:08,013 --> 00:07:10,175
just like an instantaneous transportation from one

131
00:07:10,195 --> 00:07:12,658
location to another location gives you a position curve like

132
00:07:12,699 --> 00:07:12,859
this.

133
00:07:13,796 --> 00:07:18,540
Number 11, just be creative with teleportation preview and other types of motion. There are

