00:12:58,333 --> 00:13:03,255
of people yet, but think about, you know, it sounds strange, like if I reach out, my hand

225
00:13:03,315 --> 00:13:04,715
goes way off to the back of the room.

226
00:13:05,095 --> 00:13:09,597
The reality is the motor cortex is very plastic and the brain adapts very quickly to these

227
00:13:09,657 --> 00:13:13,899
kinds of ideas. We even played around with experiments where when you're close by

228
00:13:14,019 --> 00:13:18,241
everything is one, is scaled one to one, but as you reach beyond a threshold you basically

229
00:13:18,261 --> 00:13:21,603
get go go gadget arms and they like extend out to the other side of the room and you can grab

230
00:13:21,643 --> 00:13:26,065
things. And this, or they kind of like turn into laser pointers. These are great ways to

231
00:13:26,105 --> 00:13:30,627
allow you to access a larger physical space or maybe I guess a larger virtual space without

232
00:13:30,687 --> 00:13:33,028
moving beyond that useful physical space.

233
00:13:33,922 --> 00:13:40,710
Next up, use haptics. One of the rules we try to operate by is when visuals, audios and haptics

234
00:13:41,030 --> 00:13:45,535
all come together, that's when the feeling is really magical. That's what really completes

235
00:13:45,575 --> 00:13:50,800
the feeling of immersion. I know haptics aren't available on every platform, but when they're

236
00:13:50,840 --> 00:13:52,382
there, please take advantage of them.

237
00:13:53,230 --> 00:13:56,915
Next up, this category is environments. Simple thing. We

238
00:13:56,995 --> 00:13:59,558
love huge spaces. This is another one where you don't need

239
00:13:59,578 --> 00:14:02,302
to be limited by reality. You have vaulted ceilings and

240
00:14:02,402 --> 00:14:06,066
infinite stairways and towering ruins. These places are so

241
00:14:06,126 --> 00:14:08,629
compelling to humanity. But, we have to be careful. We have to

242
00:14:09,110 --> 00:14:14,613
with those large spaces, still divide up your world into smaller spaces that fit into your

243
00:14:14,653 --> 00:14:19,815
sort of physical tracking space. So if you can divide up your world in such a way that within a

244
00:14:19,936 --> 00:14:24,798
typical tracking space for one of your users, you can teleport into that space and do all the

245
00:14:24,818 --> 00:14:28,560
interactions that you need within that space, it's going to make it a lot easier for you to

246
00:14:29,561 --> 00:14:33,283
teleport around that space. We've even divided up some worlds in interesting ways where...

247
00:14:33,963 --> 00:14:36,625
maybe on, we'll think about our tracking space.

248
00:14:36,645 --> 00:14:37,967
On that corner of the tracking space,

249
00:14:38,047 --> 00:14:40,969
if you enter that space, you get into a tramway.

250
00:14:41,009 --> 00:14:43,451
That tramway takes you up to a different corner,

251
00:14:43,551 --> 00:14:45,693
or I guess it has to be exactly the same corner

252
00:14:46,073 --> 00:14:47,174
in another tracked space.

253
00:14:47,555 --> 00:14:49,656
By laying out these transformations

254
00:14:49,696 --> 00:14:51,398
between tracking spaces creatively,

255
00:14:51,698 --> 00:14:53,660
you can really make your world feel enormous

256
00:14:54,020 --> 00:14:56,022
and your user will never have to leave,

257
00:14:56,082 --> 00:14:58,284
they'll never even feel like they need to leave

258
00:14:58,744 --> 00:14:59,905
the tracked space.

259
00:15:01,695 --> 00:15:03,696
Next, place objects in a way that keeps the player in the

260
00:15:03,736 --> 00:15:05,678
physical space. This is kind of what I was talking about before.

261
00:15:05,998 --> 00:15:08,719
So here's an example one. Let's say you're playing a game of

262
00:15:08,780 --> 00:15:11,481
golf. So you hit the golf ball, it's over there, I want to

263
00:15:11,521 --> 00:15:15,524
teleport to my golf ball. The typical thought process is, oh,

264
00:15:15,564 --> 00:15:17,925
I'll teleport such that that ball is right in front of me.

265
00:15:18,286 --> 00:15:22,268
Now, if you modify that ever so slightly and instead teleport

266
00:15:22,288 --> 00:15:24,910
the ball to the center of the room, you might need to take a

267
00:15:24,950 --> 00:15:27,271
couple steps to get in front of that ball again, but you're

268
00:15:27,412 --> 00:15:29,293
never going to leave your tracking space.

269
00:15:29,673 --> 00:15:33,874
In contrast, if you teleport the ball to right in front of you, you're building up small

270
00:15:33,914 --> 00:15:36,574
amounts of error over time and eventually you're going to run into your physical wall.

271
00:15:36,914 --> 00:15:41,735
So just think about that. These are subtle differences. Number 26, texture everything,

272
00:15:41,876 --> 00:15:45,456
even if it's just subtle noise. I think we've all had the experience where we have false

273
00:15:45,516 --> 00:15:50,517
convergence on a chain link fence or something, a repetitive pattern where you sort of have a

274
00:15:50,597 --> 00:15:52,318
hard time figuring out the depth of something.

275
00:15:52,758 --> 00:15:54,639
In VR, when we have untextured surfaces,

276
00:15:54,920 --> 00:15:57,281
we almost never encounter these untextured surfaces

277
00:15:57,321 --> 00:15:57,822
in real life.

278
00:15:57,842 --> 00:16:00,023
There are always fingerprint smudges or scratches

279
00:16:00,063 --> 00:16:00,544
or something.

280
00:16:00,924 --> 00:16:03,166
Give everything a little bit of a subtle noise texture

281
00:16:03,486 --> 00:16:04,887
just to allow your eyes to focus.

282
00:16:05,764 --> 00:16:10,427
Number 27, show the physical bounds in the virtual world. We all know when we're using

283
00:16:10,447 --> 00:16:14,090
something like Vive, we can see the edges of where the world is. We have that little glowing

284
00:16:14,150 --> 00:16:19,194
rectangle. When we get close to the wall, we have our chaperone grid. Don't make the user

285
00:16:19,214 --> 00:16:23,458
have to get that close to know where they are. That information is generally exposed by the

286
00:16:23,538 --> 00:16:27,881
API. Put something in your virtual world that represents that and nobody will even be tempted

287
00:16:27,901 --> 00:16:28,882
to go beyond those bounds.

288
00:16:29,821 --> 00:16:34,426
This is an easy one. Number 28. Everyone loves particles. Just put them in everywhere because

289
00:16:34,446 --> 00:16:39,090
they're freaking awesome. I've seen so many experiences that we spend weeks on and

290
00:16:39,150 --> 00:16:44,195
somebody will just say, oh, man, I love the rain. It took like ten seconds in unity. Just

291
00:16:44,235 --> 00:16:49,000
put particles everywhere. All right. Scale. Scale is such an incredibly powerful tool in

292
00:16:49,020 --> 00:16:50,502
VR that I wanted to have a whole section on it.

293
00:16:51,022 --> 00:16:54,866
Number one, accurate scale really matters. This is one of the reasons to start prototyping

294
00:16:54,926 --> 00:16:59,831
in VR immediately. Because if that door is 20% shorter than it's supposed to be, you

295
00:16:59,972 --> 00:17:06,338
immediately notice. And there are also very powerful things that you can do to use scale.

296
00:17:06,699 --> 00:17:09,341
Scale can convey power or vulnerability.

297
00:17:09,742 --> 00:17:13,564
So, you know, whether you're Godzilla size and marching through the streets of Tokyo or you're

298
00:17:13,624 --> 00:17:17,247
tiny and you really feel, you're feeling what it's like to be, for instance, at the side of a

299
00:17:17,307 --> 00:17:23,331
blue whale, scale can be used to convey very powerful emotional experiences. And even very

300
00:17:23,391 --> 00:17:27,634
subtle changes can have an effect. We found that if we have two, if we're doing a co‑

301
00:17:27,674 --> 00:17:32,538
presence situation where we have two vibes in different rooms and the rooms are calibrated

302
00:17:32,658 --> 00:17:36,481
ever so slightly off so that one floor is a little higher than the other floor.

303
00:17:36,921 --> 00:17:41,543
those two players, if they know each other in real life, will immediately notice the height

304
00:17:41,583 --> 00:17:45,444
difference in virtual reality. You can use this in really interesting ways, too. You can make

305
00:17:45,504 --> 00:17:49,246
everyone the same height, you can deliberately make someone taller, you can make it so that

306
00:17:49,306 --> 00:17:56,369
somebody's, their virtual head is a little bit, a little bit on top of where their physical

307
00:17:56,409 --> 00:17:58,650
head is, which means everyone looks taller to you.

308
00:17:59,690 --> 00:18:00,972
or you can make everyone look shorter to you.

309
00:18:00,992 --> 00:18:03,174
There are all kinds of interesting things that you can do

310
00:18:03,574 --> 00:18:04,836
that shape the social,

311
00:18:05,256 --> 00:18:07,018
like kind of the social shape of the world

312
00:18:07,058 --> 00:18:07,639
that you're working in.

313
00:18:09,186 --> 00:18:12,949
And then use scale as a tool. This is a little bit of an extension of the dollhouse example

314
00:18:12,969 --> 00:18:16,111
that I showed earlier. One of the pieces that we have in this dollhouse is what we call our

315
00:18:16,151 --> 00:18:20,214
little chess piece. You can put that into the dollhouse, teleport down and shrink down and

316
00:18:20,254 --> 00:18:24,877
see that dollhouse from a doll's size and walk through that. It really just gives you a

317
00:18:25,318 --> 00:18:29,120
really powerful feeling of being able to manipulate and then see from the inside.

318
00:18:31,628 --> 00:18:36,313
32, when you change scale, don't forget to change other things around scale. Physics and

319
00:18:36,433 --> 00:18:41,879
audio. Physics is a really tricky one. If it's a single player experience and you're

320
00:18:41,899 --> 00:18:46,144
teleporting between different sizes, you sort of expect physics to behave, for acceleration

321
00:18:46,184 --> 00:18:51,329
to be at 9.8 meters per second squared regardless of what size you're at. So it should be relative

322
00:18:51,369 --> 00:18:52,030
to your size.

323
00:18:52,490 --> 00:18:56,732
Now this isn't always possible. If you're in a co-presence scenario and you have one giant

324
00:18:56,772 --> 00:19:01,754
player and one tiny player, physics is going to have to be different for those two players. My

325
00:19:01,794 --> 00:19:07,616
suggestion would be to anchor physics to seem correct for the smallest player. Because it's a

326
00:19:07,716 --> 00:19:11,857
lot less disconcerting to be that giant and see things kind of moving slowly through the air

327
00:19:12,237 --> 00:19:16,679
than to be that tiny player and see things moving incredibly quickly. You know, 980 meters

328
00:19:16,699 --> 00:19:19,000
per second squared just doesn't feel right.

329
00:19:20,041 --> 00:19:26,733
Audio also, if you have a little tiny player, pitch up their audio. It just feels right to

330
00:19:26,753 --> 00:19:28,095
people. It feels more immersive that way.

331
00:19:29,543 --> 00:19:33,944
All right, co‑ presence. This is a tricky one. Number one, players expect something to

332
00:19:33,984 --> 00:19:38,525
happen when they touch. Anyone who has experimented with co‑ presence scenarios and

333
00:19:38,745 --> 00:19:42,266
created some prototypes in this area, they've seen a lot of these same behaviors. The first

334
00:19:42,326 --> 00:19:46,807
thing players do when they get into co‑ presence is they try to touch each other. So

335
00:19:46,847 --> 00:19:49,508
something should happen. A shower of sparks, a high five.

336
00:19:50,789 --> 00:19:52,390
But there's also, like, you know,

337
00:19:52,430 --> 00:19:53,731
there are some negative consequences

338
00:19:54,111 --> 00:19:56,293
that come from this desire to touch each other in VR.

339
00:19:57,034 --> 00:19:58,895
And we need to figure out better ways of dealing with those.

340
00:19:59,316 --> 00:20:01,798
One of those is that we don't want to reward bad behavior.

341
00:20:02,638 --> 00:20:03,859
So this is an example where we have

342
00:20:03,879 --> 00:20:05,000
a couple dogs playing poker.

343
00:20:06,161 --> 00:20:07,382
And we, you know, this is,

344
00:20:07,622 --> 00:20:09,304
poker, there are very specific rules

345
00:20:09,344 --> 00:20:10,405
about how things should work.

346
00:20:11,766 --> 00:20:13,808
And here we have, you know, we have the opponent win.

347
00:20:15,011 --> 00:20:17,673
and the other one kind of walks over to take retribution.

348
00:20:17,793 --> 00:20:19,213
And we have very simple things here.

349
00:20:19,474 --> 00:20:22,455
The world fades to gray, the audio dims down,

350
00:20:22,996 --> 00:20:24,496
there's a glowing sphere that tells you

351
00:20:24,536 --> 00:20:25,717
where you're supposed to go back to,

352
00:20:25,777 --> 00:20:27,198
and you disappear from the world.

353
00:20:27,438 --> 00:20:28,859
Now, none of these are terrible punishments.

354
00:20:28,899 --> 00:20:30,460
It's not like a flashing sign that says,

355
00:20:30,520 --> 00:20:31,660
please return to your seat.

356
00:20:32,161 --> 00:20:33,261
It's just enough to say,

357
00:20:33,581 --> 00:20:34,762
you're playing this experience wrong,

358
00:20:34,842 --> 00:20:36,343
please go back to where you were supposed to be.

359
00:20:36,683 --> 00:20:37,924
And that's really all that it takes.

360
00:20:38,244 --> 00:20:40,946
So just very slight negative influences

361
00:20:40,986 --> 00:20:41,986
for antisocial behavior.

362
00:20:42,847 --> 00:20:47,613
On the flip side, of course, do reward pro-social interactions. If you reward pro-social

363
00:20:47,633 --> 00:20:52,278
interactions, a shower of sparks when you do a high five but not when you punch the face,

364
00:20:52,959 --> 00:20:56,864
people will do the pro-social interactions and not the negative interactions.

365
00:20:58,353 --> 00:21:00,475
Number 36, enforce social boundaries.

366
00:21:00,575 --> 00:21:02,396
So people, and this is, you know,

367
00:21:02,596 --> 00:21:05,019
people will do this thinking that it's a very innocent thing.

368
00:21:05,059 --> 00:21:07,661
The first time people go into a co-present scenario,

369
00:21:07,941 --> 00:21:09,382
they'll say, I wonder what it feels like

370
00:21:09,422 --> 00:21:10,743
when I stand inside your body.

371
00:21:10,824 --> 00:21:12,225
Because you know, this is something you can't do

372
00:21:12,265 --> 00:21:13,005
in the physical world.

373
00:21:13,946 --> 00:21:15,287
This can be really uncomfortable.

374
00:21:15,588 --> 00:21:17,850
It is completely innocently intentioned,

375
00:21:18,230 --> 00:21:20,452
but it can feel very uncomfortable for the other person.

376
00:21:20,492 --> 00:21:22,073
So we just need to anticipate this.

377
00:21:22,493 --> 00:21:27,275
Especially right now at the beginning of VR, a lot of people are having their very first VR

378
00:21:27,315 --> 00:21:31,696
experiences. If a lot of those experiences are bad, we are shooting ourselves in the foot. We

379
00:21:31,716 --> 00:21:36,597
need to be the ones responsible for creating a healthy ecosystem. So simple things, you

380
00:21:36,617 --> 00:21:41,879
know, make the opponent's body disappear as they enter your personal space bubble. Let people

381
00:21:41,939 --> 00:21:46,620
define their own personal space bubbles. Allow someone to ban someone from a room or make

382
00:21:46,660 --> 00:21:51,661
them invisible. We really need to think about, you know, innocent behaviors are bad enough.

383
00:21:52,122 --> 00:21:53,943
or can be bad enough, we really need to think about

384
00:21:53,984 --> 00:21:57,006
when people are intentionally trying to be

385
00:21:57,707 --> 00:21:59,309
negative antisocial behaviors in VR.

386
00:22:00,850 --> 00:22:02,452
Number 37, this is an easy one.

387
00:22:02,492 --> 00:22:04,273
Voice chat really multiplies immersion.

388
00:22:04,594 --> 00:22:06,696
We find that if you have two people in different rooms,

389
00:22:08,434 --> 00:22:13,201
other people who are not in the vibe can still continue a conversation with those people until

390
00:22:13,521 --> 00:22:17,267
they're connected with each other by voice. At that point, the rest of the world just falls

391
00:22:17,327 --> 00:22:22,595
away. Everything else becomes noise. Voice chat really, really increases immersion.

392
00:22:24,597 --> 00:22:28,639
38, put shared objects at the center of the space. We did a couple different versions of a

393
00:22:28,679 --> 00:22:32,600
co‑president's music making scenario. In one, all the instruments were on the outside of

394
00:22:32,620 --> 00:22:36,481
the room. And what we found is that people would kind of just like do their own thing. Like

395
00:22:36,501 --> 00:22:39,543
they could hear their friend behind them doing something else, but they weren't playing

396
00:22:39,563 --> 00:22:39,923
together.

397
00:22:40,763 --> 00:22:43,365
Some of this has to do with the field of view that you have in VR.

398
00:22:43,665 --> 00:22:46,987
If that other person isn't within your field of view, you kind of just feel like they're

399
00:22:47,007 --> 00:22:47,527
somewhere else.

400
00:22:47,867 --> 00:22:51,009
If you instead put all those instruments at the center of the room so that if you're playing

401
00:22:51,129 --> 00:22:54,491
one and your friends are playing another, you're forced to face each other, people

402
00:22:54,511 --> 00:22:55,571
start making music together.

403
00:22:55,972 --> 00:22:57,592
It was just a complete difference in behavior.

404
00:22:58,486 --> 00:23:02,989
Number 39, think about asymmetric experiences. This is more of a thought experience. When we

405
00:23:03,029 --> 00:23:07,252
get started in VR, there aren't going to be a whole lot of VR devices out there. What we're

406
00:23:07,272 --> 00:23:11,334
going to need to do is find a way to involve the people who aren't in the headset in the

407
00:23:11,374 --> 00:23:15,837
experience of the other people. So we've done some pretty crazy experiments where we have

408
00:23:16,137 --> 00:23:20,000
maybe one person in a daydream, but everybody else can be on their phone and be connected to

409
00:23:20,040 --> 00:23:20,660
that experience.

410
00:23:21,381 --> 00:23:25,524
and maybe they're talking by voice. We did one last week where the person in the Daydream

411
00:23:25,544 --> 00:23:29,546
headset is a cat trying to brush its teeth but it has no control over its arms. It can only

412
00:23:29,566 --> 00:23:33,909
turn right and left. The person on the controller is actually the one controlling the arms

413
00:23:34,330 --> 00:23:38,433
with forward kinematics and they have to grab the toothbrush and get it to the mouth. I know

414
00:23:38,453 --> 00:23:42,475
this is crazy but these kinds of experiences are going to be really important for bringing

415
00:23:42,535 --> 00:23:46,458
people into the fold in VR. All right, next up, avatars.

416
00:23:49,012 --> 00:23:52,414
full body avatars, I mean avatars are tricky. This is the place where I know people are going to

417
00:23:52,434 --> 00:23:57,578
disagree with me. That's totally fine. In our experience what we found is that full body

418
00:23:57,618 --> 00:24:02,002
avatars, they can work very well if you're looking at another full body avatar. But when you

419
00:24:02,042 --> 00:24:06,325
look down at your feet and you see them oriented in a different way than your physical feet are,

420
00:24:06,786 --> 00:24:10,408
people find it uncomfortable. And the further down you go on your body, the more

421
00:24:10,609 --> 00:24:14,512
uncomfortable that gets. So maybe you can find a good way to simulate the elbows, but when

422
00:24:14,532 --> 00:24:15,352
you get down to the legs,

423
00:24:16,113 --> 00:24:19,396
There's a good chance you just want to make those disappear when you're looking at your own avatar.

424
00:24:19,416 --> 00:24:21,238
They can be visible to everybody else, that's okay.

425
00:24:23,283 --> 00:24:29,288
41. Eyes are so important. Forward staring non blinking eyes are so creepy. They're really

426
00:24:29,388 --> 00:24:33,371
simple things you can do to give those eyes a little bit of a brain. We literally call it the

427
00:24:33,471 --> 00:24:39,076
eye brain plug in on our side. These eyes are really simple. They blink randomly. As you start

428
00:24:39,116 --> 00:24:44,580
to turn your head, the eyes move forward. They accelerate that motion to anticipate the

429
00:24:44,600 --> 00:24:48,063
direction that they're going. It just makes them more lively. There are some other great

430
00:24:48,083 --> 00:24:49,844
demos I saw yesterday where people were

431
00:24:50,285 --> 00:24:56,229
creating, they were setting up the third party or their NPCs to look, basically what was

432
00:24:56,270 --> 00:25:00,133
appropriate to look at, kind of action. So you don't want them to just stare, but you might

433
00:25:00,173 --> 00:25:04,256
want them to kind of move their eyes between areas of interest in the space.

434
00:25:07,485 --> 00:25:11,407
Next up, when you pick up an item, that item can become your controller. This is a simple one.

435
00:25:11,427 --> 00:25:17,069
I've seen this done pretty well. Rather than crowding your visual space with both your

436
00:25:17,089 --> 00:25:20,830
virtual hands and also the item you're picking up, just make that item that you've picked up

437
00:25:20,890 --> 00:25:22,491
your controller and make everything else disappear.

438
00:25:23,771 --> 00:25:28,913
beware of the uncanny valley. We all instinctively know this rule. But the thing is, it's so

439
00:25:29,093 --> 00:25:33,975
easy to follow in VR. The reality is when you're in co‑present situations, you don't need a

440
00:25:34,115 --> 00:25:39,777
particularly realistic head or hands to convey a ton of emotion. So here you can just see,

441
00:25:39,817 --> 00:25:45,418
like, the emotion of these players comes through so clearly. You don't need gesture. It just

442
00:25:45,458 --> 00:25:48,880
comes through. Just send a couple of transforms over the network and you're golden.

443
00:25:50,516 --> 00:25:55,760
All right, user interfaces, another really tough area in VR. Simple one, avoid user interfaces

